family__almaMater__nota: British embryologist, first to grow a whole organ, a thymus, inside an animal
Scottish pathologist, discovered the importance of programmed cell death and coined the term apoptosis
British transplant surgeon, performed the first ever kidney transplant in the UK at the Edinburgh Royal Infirmary in 1960.
Led the team that discovered CpG Islands and MECP2, received the 2016 Shaw Prize in Life Science and Medicine
Norwegian neuroscientist, discovered entorhinal grid cells, awarded the 2014 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine
British embryologist and synthetic biologist, first to grow a kidney from self-organizing stem cells
Scottish ophthalmologist, described the Argyll Robertson pupil a sign of neurosyphilis
Welsh psychiatrist, Chief Medical Officer of Scotland from 1991–1996
Scottish physician, first demonstrated artificial refrigeration, founder of the Glasgow Medical School, advocate of holistic medical consultation
British paediatrician, President of the British Paediatric Association  and awarded the Military Cross during the Second World War
Scottish physician, CEO of the Medical Research Council 2010–present
American biochemist, discovered oxytocin, awarded the 1955 Nobel Prize in Chemistry
Scottish neuroscientist, developed the Morris water navigation task
English physiologist, regarded as the founder of endocrinology, discovered adrenaline, coined the terms endocrine and insulin
Scottish embryologist, first to clone a mammal, a Finn Dorset lamb named Dolly, received the 2008 Shaw Prize in Life Science and Medicine
Scottish physician, introduced Charles Darwin to biology, created a chart to display the varying sizes of the primary chancre in syphilis.
Scottish physician, first described the blue whale, founder of the Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh
British physician, pioneered the treatment of tuberculosis, which was known as the Edinburgh method.
British pharmacologist, discovered Substance P, a neuropeptide
Scottish physician, first to introduce clinical teaching in Edinburgh known as the "Edinburgh method"
Scottish surgeon, invented Mackintosh, conducted the first exarticulation of the hip, known for Syme's amputation
Scottish anatomist, President of the Anatomical Society of Great Britain and Ireland
Scottish biologist, discovered penicillin, awarded the 1945 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine
British chemist, identified tyramine, contributed to the synthesis of thyroxine and Vitamin B1
Scottish surgeon, performed lumbar sympathectomy on King George VI to treat his vascular disease

Scottish surgeon, developed antiseptic surgery using carbolic acid to sterilise surgical instruments

field__honorificSuffix__text: The first duty of a member of Parliament is to do what they think in their faithful and disinterested judgement is right and necessary for the honour and safety of Great Britain. The second duty is to their constituents, of whom they are the representative but not the delegate. Burke's famous declaration on this subject is well known. It is only in the third place that their duty to party organisation or programme takes rank. All these three loyalties should be observed, but there is no doubt of the order in which they stand under any healthy manifestation of democracy.
